Clearly, every amalgamation can be viewed as a special bi-amalgamation, since $A\bowtie^fJ= A\bowtie^{{{\operatorname{id}}_{A}}, f}(f^{-1}(J),J)$.
Accordingly, Theorem~\ref{arith} covers the special case of amalgamations, as recorded below.



\begin{corollary}\label{arith-c1}
Under the above notation, we have:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $A\bowtie^{f}J$ is a chained ring if and only if both $A$ and $f(A)+J$ are chained rings and $J=0$ or $f^{-1}(J)=0$.
\item   $A\bowtie^{f}J$ is arithmetical if and only if both  $A$ and $f(A)+J$ are arithmetical and, for every ${\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}\in{\operatorname{Max}}(A,f^{-1}(J))$, $J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}=0$ or $f_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}^{-1}\left(J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}\right)=0$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{corollary}




\begin{remark}\label{arith-r2-1}
Recently, Finocchiaro proved the following result for the transfer of the arithmetical property to amalgamations: "\emph{Assume that, for each ${\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}\in{\operatorname{Max}}(A, f^{-1}(J))$, either $f_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}$ is surjective or $f_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}^{-1}\left(J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}\right)\not=0$. Then, $A\bowtie^{f}J$ is arithmetical if and only if $A$ is arithmetical, $J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}=0$ for each  ${\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}\in{\operatorname{Max}}(A,f^{-1}(J))$, and for any ${\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'\in{\operatorname{Max}}(B)$ not containing $J$, the ideals of $B_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'}$ are totally ordered by inclusion}" \cite[Proposition 4.10]{Fin}. Corollary~\ref{arith-c1} covers this result due to the basic fact that if $f_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}$ is surjective and $J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}\not=0$ then $f_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}^{-1}\left(J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}\right)\not=0$; combined with the two-type maximal ideal structure of $A\bowtie^{f}J$ (cf.  \cite[Proposition 2.6]{DFF2} and \cite[Proposition 2.5]{Fin}); precisely,  $A_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}\cong (A\bowtie^{f}J)_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}\bowtie^{f}J}$ when $J_{S_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}}}=0$ and $B_{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'}\cong (A\bowtie^{f}J)_{\overline{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'}}$ where $\overline{{\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'}=\big\{(a, f(a)+j)\in A\bowtie^{f}J \mid f(a)+j\in {\operatorname{\mathfrak{m}}}'\big\}$.
\end{remark}




\begin{remark}\label{arith-r3}
Assume $J\not=0$. Then Remark~\ref{arith-r2} combined with \cite[Corollary 4.6]{KLT} yield: \emph{$A\bowtie^{f}J$ is a chained ring (resp., valuation domain) if and only if $f^{-1}(J)=0$ and $f(A)+J$ is a chained ring (resp., valuation domain)}.
\end{remark}

